              <tr class='athing comtr ' id='16524452'><td>
            <table border='0'>  <tr>    <td class='ind'><img src="s.gif" height="1" width="0"></td><td valign="top" class="votelinks"><center><a id='up_16524452' href='vote?id=16524452&amp;how=up&amp;goto=item%3Fid%3D16523786'><div class='votearrow' title='upvote'></div></a></center></td><td class="default"><div style="margin-top:2px; margin-bottom:-10px;"><span class="comhead">
          <a href="user?id=resource0x" class="hnuser">resource0x</a> <span class="age"><a href="item?id=16524452">13 hours ago</a></span> <span id="unv_16524452"></span><span class="par"></span> <a class="togg" n="22" href="javascript:void(0)" onclick="return toggle(event, 16524452)"></a>          <span class='storyon'></span>
                  </span></div><br><div class="comment">
                  <span class="c00">from the article:
The volume of the unit d-sphere goes to 0 as d grows! A high dimensional unit sphere encloses almost no volume!<p>Maybe I&#x27;m nitpicking, but this interpretation is not accurate IMO. Volume of N-dimensional sphere is measured is different units than that of (N-1)-dimensional sphere. E.g. one is m^5, and another is m^4. Comparing values measured in different units is not the best idea. It would be better worded as : the ratio of volume of N-dimensional sphere to the volume of same-dimensional cube approaches zero when N goes to infinity. But this is not a counter-intuitive statement.<span>
              </span><div class='reply'>        <p><font size="1">
                      <u><a href="reply?id=16524452&amp;goto=item%3Fid%3D16523786%2316524452">reply</a></u>
                  </font>
      </div></td></tr>
